Profiling Aircraft On Time Preformance for climate-friendly planning.¶

by Obum Onwudiwe¶

Introduction¶

Air travel is vital to the world economy and in recent years the impact of aviation related activities on climate change has gained prominence. Organizations are pushing for more regulatory controls on such activities to curb the effect of climate change and global warming. This project aims to gain insights to short term strategies that can be implemented to aid solving this challenge, by profiling delays associated with air travel with the aim of shaping the conversation among airlines and regulatory bodies to aid climate friendly planning around minimizing delays.

The dataset contains scheduled and actual departure and arrival times for 2005 and 2008, reported by certified U.S. air carriers that account for at least one percent of domestic scheduled passenger revenues. The data is collected by the Office of Airline Information, Bureau of Transportation Statistics (BTS). Reporting carriers are required to (or voluntarily) report on-time data for flights they operate: on-time arrival and departure data for non-stop domestic flights by month and year, by carrier and by origin and destination airport. Includes scheduled and actual departure and arrival times, canceled and diverted flights, taxi-out and taxi-in times, causes of delay and cancellation, air time, and non-stop distance.

The airlines report the causes of delay in broad categories: Air Carrier, National Aviation System, Weather, Late-Arriving Aircraft and Security. The cancellation codes are the same - A (Carrier), B (weather), C (NAS) and D(security).

i. Air Carrier: The cause of the cancellation or delay was due to circumstances within the airline's control (e.g. maintenance or crew problems, aircraft cleaning, baggage loading, fueling, etc.).

ii. Extreme Weather: Significant meteorological conditions (actual or forecasted) that, in the judgment of the carrier, delays or prevents the operation of a flight such as tornado, blizzard or hurricane.

iii. National Aviation System (NAS): Delays and cancellations attributable to the national aviation system that refer to a broad set of conditions, such as non-extreme weather conditions, airport operations, heavy traffic volume, and air traffic control.

iv. Late-arriving aircraft: A previous flight with same aircraft arrived late, causing the present flight to depart late.

v. Security: Delays or cancellations caused by evacuation of a terminal or concourse, re-boarding of aircraft because of security breach, inoperative screening equipment and/or long lines in excess of 29 minutes at screening areas.

Preliminary Wrangling¶

Preliminary wrangling involves importing libraries, files, making copies and data wrangling such as dropping duplicates, filling null values and converting data to appropriate types. A timedelta is applied to the Day of Week column to represent weekday numbers with weekday names.

What is the structure of your dataset?¶

There are 1,048,575 flight records in each dataset with 29 features each. Most variables are numeric in nature, but the variables Unique Carrier, Tail num, Origin and Destination are string variables.

What is/are the main feature(s) of interest in your dataset?¶

The features that represent the causes and durations for why an aircraft was not operated as scheduled (delay). The arrival and departure delay features together with the cause of the delay including late aircraft arrival, carrier delay, weather, security.

What features in the dataset do you think will help support your investigation into your feature(s) of interest?¶

The relationship between the delay cause and duration will be analyzed to discover the relative magnitude of its effect from an associated airline, airport and aircraft, as these are the systems which can cause or suffer a delay.

Univariate Exploration¶

This is a representation of the count of each cause of delays, not the duration of the delays. It is scaled to the proportion of each delay to the total count. NAS delays represents a broad range of factors. NAS delays show the highest decrease from 2005 to 2008, while late aircraft delays show the highest increase. These delay causes cut across both arrivals and departures.

How can we account and understand these changes at an aircraft, airline and airport level? and in what phase of the flight? Better planning can aid climate friendly strategies; features like these can be monitored to drive behaviours and decisions that can help to measure and reduce the impact of aviation related activities on the climate.

The large range of values for the elapsed flight times and delay times required a log transformation of the x axis for the various dataframes. Melting the delay features enabled observations of the variations in how the various delay causes affect the flight time. The changes in number of delays varied according to the causes.

Airports of departure that recorded at least 3000 delays from various airlines with above 15 mins durations. Airline OO doesnt perform as well in airports EWR, SFO and MEM. The heatmap provides a broader view of how each delay cause impacts the various airlines and can be traced to what phase of the flight envelope (arrival or departure) by the airport where the event occurred.

Conclusions¶

This visualization profiling of the delay cause, durations and phase of occurrence has generated insights into how airlines are affected by various delays with the corresponding location of occurrence. The effect of average and individual values can be misleading when not put in context of the dataset. Weather delays may appear to be the leading cause of delays when aggregated; It however turns out airlnes are more impacted by other delays cumulatively but when a weather delay occurs, it may last longer.

It can be useful for planning of scheduled flight times, to improve the on time performance of aircraft at various airports and reduce the impact of wasted time and resources which delays cause, as the impact of aviation related activities on the climate can be reduced with short term stategies.
